SIMPLE: obituary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obituary
<hw>O*bit"u*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Obit</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the death of a person or
persons; <as>as, an <ex>obituary</ex> notice; <ex>obituary</ex>
poetry.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>obituary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: obituary
<hw>o*bit"u*a*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Obituaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>obituaire</ets>. See <er>Obit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
which pertains to, or is called forth by, the obit or death of a person;
esp., an account of a deceased person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <def>A notice of the death
of a person, published in a newspaper or other periodical, accompanied
by a biographical sketch which may be brief or extended; <as>as, the
funeral director arranged placed an <ex>obituary</ex> in the local
paper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The section of a newspaper in which
obituaries{2} are printed; <as>as, I saw the notice of his death in the
<ex>obituaries</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A list of the dead, or a
register of anniversary days when service is performed for the
dead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Object</ent>⟦br⟧
